<!-- ════ DEEP DIVE ════ -->
<section class="section" id="deep">
  <div class="s-inner">
    <div class="s-tag">Detailed Profiles</div>
    <h2 class="s-title">Know Each Qualification<br/><em>In Depth</em></h2>
    <div class="divider"></div>
    <div class="deep-grid">

      <!-- IGCSE -->
      <article class="dcard igcse reveal rd1">
        <div class="dcard-head igcse">
          <div class="dcard-abbr">IGCSE</div>
          <div class="dcard-fullname">International General Certificate of Secondary Education</div>
          <div class="dcard-tagline">The world's most popular international secondary qualification</div>
        </div>
        <div class="dcard-body">
          <h4>What It Is</h4>
          <p>IGCSE is administered by Cambridge Assessment International Education (part of the University of Cambridge). It is taken in over 160 countries and accepted by universities worldwide. Students typically sit 5–10 subjects, with results graded A*–G. Emphasis is placed on understanding, analysis, and independent thinking rather than memorisation.</p>
          <h4>Assessment</h4>
          <p>Combination of written examinations, coursework, practical assessments, and oral components depending on subject. Questions typically require extended writing, analysis, and evaluation rather than simple recall.</p>
          <h4>Subjects Available</h4>
          <ul><li>English Language &amp; Literature, Mathematics, Sciences (Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Combined)</li><li>Humanities: History, Geography, Economics, Business Studies, Global Perspectives</li><li>Languages, Arts, Computing, Physical Education and more (70+ subjects total)</li></ul>
          <h4>Pathway After IGCSE</h4>
          <p>Students typically proceed to Cambridge International AS &amp; A Levels, IB Diploma, Foundation programmes, or BTEC. This leads directly to university application worldwide.</p>
          <div class="pro-con"><div class="pros-box"><h5>Strengths</h5><ul><li>Recognised in 160+ countries</li><li>Develops critical thinking &amp; English</li><li>Flexible subject selection</li><li>Homeschool / private candidate possible</li><li>Strong preparation for A Levels</li></ul></div><div class="cons-box"><h5>Considerations</h5><ul><li>Higher school fees than SPM/STPM</li><li>Not direct pathway for IPTA</li><li>Requires strong English base</li></ul></div></div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- SPM -->
      <article class="dcard spm reveal rd2">
        <div class="dcard-head spm">
          <div class="dcard-abbr">SPM</div>
          <div class="dcard-fullname">Sijil Pelajaran Malaysia</div>
          <div class="dcard-tagline">Malaysia's national lower secondary examination</div>
        </div>
        <div class="dcard-body">
          <h4>What It Is</h4>
          <p>SPM is Malaysia's national secondary school examination, administered by Lembaga Peperiksaan Malaysia (LPM). It is compulsory for students in government and national-type schools, taken at the end of Form 5. Results are graded A+–G per subject, and the overall result is used for IPTA entry through the UPU application system.</p>
          <h4>Assessment</h4>
          <p>Primarily written examinations with some school-based assessment (PBS) components. Greater emphasis on recall and structured responses compared to IGCSE, though recent reforms have introduced more HOTS (Higher Order Thinking Skills) questions.</p>
          <h4>Core Subjects</h4>
          <ul><li>Compulsory: Bahasa Malaysia, English, Mathematics, History, Moral/Islamic Studies</li><li>Electives: Sciences, Additional Mathematics, Accounts, Economics, Arts, Languages</li><li>Students typically sit 8–12 subjects</li></ul>
          <h4>Pathway After SPM</h4>
          <p>STPM (Form 6), Matriculation (Matrikulasi), Foundation programmes (ASASI), Diploma, A Levels, or direct entry to some private universities. STPM/Matriculation required for IPTA entry.</p>
          <div class="pro-con"><div class="pros-box"><h5>Strengths</h5><ul><li>Free / very low cost (government school)</li><li>Gateway to Malaysian IPTA</li><li>Widely understood by Malaysian employers</li><li>Strong Bahasa Malaysia foundation</li></ul></div><div class="cons-box"><h5>Considerations</h5><ul><li>Limited international recognition</li><li>English proficiency less emphasised</li><li>Less flexibility in subjects</li></ul></div></div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- STPM -->
      <article class="dcard stpm reveal rd3">
        <div class="dcard-head stpm">
          <div class="dcard-abbr">STPM</div>
          <div class="dcard-fullname">Sijil Tinggi Persekolahan Malaysia</div>
          <div class="dcard-tagline">Malaysia's pre-university qualification, equivalent to A Levels</div>
        </div>
        <div class="dcard-body">
          <h4>What It Is</h4>
          <p>STPM is administered by Majlis Peperiksaan Malaysia (MPM) and is considered equivalent to the British A Level. It is a pre-university qualification taken after SPM in Form 6 (Lower and Upper Six). Results use a CGPA system. STPM is the primary qualification for entry into Malaysian public universities (IPTA) and is one of the most affordable pre-university routes available.</p>
          <h4>Assessment</h4>
          <p>Semester-based assessment: three semesters with school-based assessment (coursework/practicals) contributing to each semester's grade, plus final external examinations. CGPA across all semesters forms the final result used for university applications.</p>
          <h4>Subjects</h4>
          <ul><li>Students choose 3–4 subjects from streams: Science, Arts, or Technical</li><li>Compulsory: Pengajian Am (General Studies)</li><li>Examples: Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Mathematics, Economics, Accounts, Literature, History</li></ul>
          <h4>Pathway After STPM</h4>
          <p>Direct application to Malaysian public universities (UM, UKM, USM, UPM, UTM, etc.) via UPU. Also accepted by some private universities in Malaysia and some Australian institutions.</p>
          <div class="pro-con"><div class="pros-box"><h5>Strengths</h5><ul><li>Very affordable (government subsidised)</li><li>Gold standard for Malaysian IPTA entry</li><li>Rigorous — A Level equivalent</li><li>Wide subject range</li></ul></div><div class="cons-box"><h5>Considerations</h5><ul><li>Must attend Form 6 (school-based)</li><li>Limited international recognition vs A Levels</li><li>Competitive — lower CGPA may limit IPTA options</li></ul></div></div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- UEC -->
      <article class="dcard uec reveal rd4">
        <div class="dcard-head uec">
          <div class="dcard-abbr">UEC</div>
          <div class="dcard-fullname">Unified Examination Certificate</div>
          <div class="dcard-tagline">The qualification of Malaysia's Chinese Independent Schools</div>
        </div>
        <div class="dcard-body">
          <h4>What It Is</h4>
          <p>UEC (统考) is administered by the United Chinese School Committees' Association of Malaysia (UCSCAM / Dong Zong). It is the qualification of Chinese Independent High Schools (华文独立中学) and is conducted primarily in Mandarin. The UEC has two levels: Junior (JUEC, equivalent to Form 3 / O Level) and Senior (SUEC, equivalent to pre-university / A Level). It is not recognised by Malaysian public universities, which has long been a contentious policy issue.</p>
          <h4>Assessment</h4>
          <p>Written examinations primarily in Mandarin Chinese. Students study a broad curriculum including Chinese, Malay, English, Mathematics, Sciences, Commerce, and Humanities — typically 16–20 subjects total across the junior and senior levels.</p>
          <h4>Subject Coverage</h4>
          <ul><li>Three languages: Chinese, Malay, English</li><li>Sciences: Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Mathematics, Additional Mathematics</li><li>Commerce: Bookkeeping/Accounts, Economics, Commerce</li><li>Humanities: History, Geography, Art</li></ul>
          <h4>Pathway After UEC</h4>
          <p>Universities in Taiwan, China, Singapore, Hong Kong, and some private Malaysian universities. Students seeking Australian university entry may need to pair UEC with other qualifications. Some UEC holders also take IGCSE or A Levels simultaneously.</p>
          <div class="pro-con"><div class="pros-box"><h5>Strengths</h5><ul><li>Strong Mandarin and trilingual education</li><li>Direct pathway to Chinese-speaking universities</li><li>Recognised in Singapore (NUS, NTU)</li><li>Comprehensive broad curriculum</li></ul></div><div class="cons-box"><h5>Considerations</h5><ul><li>NOT recognised by Malaysian public universities (IPTA)</li><li>Limited recognition in UK/USA/Canada</li><li>Fewer international study options vs IGCSE</li></ul></div></div>
        </div>
      </article>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

