<section class="section" id="faq" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/FAQPage">
  <div class="s-inner">
    <div class="s-tag">Questions &amp; Answers</div>
    <h2 class="s-title">Frequently Asked<br/><em>Questions</em></h2>
    <div class="divider"></div>
    <p class="s-lead">Common questions parents and students ask when comparing IGCSE, SPM, STPM, and UEC.</p>

    <div class="faq-list reveal">
      <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><div class="faq-q" onclick="tf(this)" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false"><span itemprop="name">What is the difference between IGCSE and SPM?</span><div class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</div></div><div class="faq-ans" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><p itemprop="text">IGCSE is an internationally recognised qualification by Cambridge Assessment International Education, taught in English, and accepted by universities in 160+ countries. SPM is Malaysia's national examination in Bahasa Malaysia, primarily for entry into Malaysian public universities. IGCSE places greater emphasis on critical thinking and written English. SPM is far cheaper as it is government-subsidised, and is the gateway to Malaysian IPTA entry.</p></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><div class="faq-q" onclick="tf(this)" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false"><span itemprop="name">Is IGCSE harder than SPM?</span><div class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</div></div><div class="faq-ans" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><p itemprop="text">IGCSE and SPM assess different competencies so a direct comparison is complex. IGCSE places greater weight on critical analysis, extended writing, and independent thinking in English, benchmarked to international standards. SPM is benchmarked to Malaysian national standards. Students who are stronger in English and analytical thinking typically find IGCSE a natural fit, while students stronger in Bahasa Malaysia may find SPM more comfortable. Neither is objectively "harder" — it depends on the individual.</p></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><div class="faq-q" onclick="tf(this)" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false"><span itemprop="name">Which qualification is best for studying abroad?</span><div class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</div></div><div class="faq-ans" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><p itemprop="text">Cambridge IGCSE (followed by A Levels) offers the broadest global university access, accepted in the UK, Australia, USA, Canada, Singapore, and 160+ countries. UEC is well-recognised in Taiwan, China, and Singapore. STPM is accepted at some Australian universities and some Commonwealth institutions. SPM has very limited direct international recognition. For the widest global options, IGCSE + A Levels is the most versatile pathway.</p></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><div class="faq-q" onclick="tf(this)" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false"><span itemprop="name">Which is cheapest — IGCSE, STPM, SPM, or UEC?</span><div class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</div></div><div class="faq-ans" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><p itemprop="text">SPM and STPM are by far the cheapest, as they are taken in government schools that are subsidised by the Malaysian government. Examination fees are minimal. UEC is taken in Chinese Independent Schools with moderate school fees. Cambridge IGCSE involves private school fees plus CAIE examination registration fees, making it significantly more expensive. However, smaller IGCSE schools like Sunrise Education in Klang maintain accessible fee structures compared to larger international schools.</p></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><div class="faq-q" onclick="tf(this)" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false"><span itemprop="name">Does IGCSE allow entry into Malaysian public universities (IPTA)?</span><div class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</div></div><div class="faq-ans" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><p itemprop="text">Cambridge IGCSE alone is not the standard pathway for Malaysian public university (IPTA) entry. IPTA entry primarily uses SPM results followed by STPM or Matriculation (Matrikulasi). However, students with IGCSE qualifications can pursue A Levels or Foundation programmes which are accepted by private universities and some public universities in Malaysia. IGCSE is primarily aimed at private university and international university entry.</p></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><div class="faq-q" onclick="tf(this)" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false"><span itemprop="name">Is UEC recognised in Malaysia?</span><div class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</div></div><div class="faq-ans" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><p itemprop="text">UEC is NOT recognised for entry into Malaysian public universities (IPTA). This has been a long-standing policy debate in Malaysia. However, many Malaysian private universities accept UEC. UEC is well-recognised internationally by universities in Taiwan, China, Singapore (NUS, NTU), and some Australian universities. Some UEC students also sit for IGCSE or A Levels to broaden their options.</p></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><div class="faq-q" onclick="tf(this)" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false"><span itemprop="name">What is STPM equivalent to internationally?</span><div class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</div></div><div class="faq-ans" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><p itemprop="text">STPM is widely considered equivalent to the British A Level standard and is sometimes called the Malaysian A Level. It is one of the world's most rigorous pre-university examinations. STPM is recognised by some Australian universities and some Commonwealth institutions. However, it does not carry the same international brand recognition as Cambridge A Levels, so for UK/USA/Canada universities, Cambridge A Levels or IB Diploma are more appropriate alternatives.</p></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><div class="faq-q" onclick="tf(this)" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false"><span itemprop="name">Can a student do both IGCSE and SPM?</span><div class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</div></div><div class="faq-ans" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><p itemprop="text">Some private schools in Malaysia offer dual-pathway programmes that prepare students for both Cambridge IGCSE and SPM examinations simultaneously. However, this is academically demanding. More commonly, students and families choose one pathway based on their goals. IGCSE students can register as private candidates for SPM if needed, though this requires significant additional preparation.</p></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><div class="faq-q" onclick="tf(this)" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false"><span itemprop="name">Which qualification do employers in Malaysia prefer?</span><div class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</div></div><div class="faq-ans" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><p itemprop="text">For Malaysian employers, what matters most is the degree/diploma the candidate holds, not the secondary school qualification. However, IGCSE and A Level backgrounds are often associated with stronger English communication skills, critical thinking, and international exposure — qualities valued by multinational companies and global firms. For government sector jobs in Malaysia, SPM/STPM pathways through IPTA are often more directly relevant. Ultimately the university degree matters far more than which secondary qualification was taken.</p></div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

